Corona Virus Data Analysis Insights Summary¶

By Shawn Tay¶

MSDS 422 Section 55¶

This analysis looks at the Corona virus data as of April 11th 2020 and finds that there is still significant risk of spread throughout the world population and that in several large countries (like the United States) death rates have not caught up with cases and there is a potential for a surge in deaths in the coming days.

The analysis looks at the data to gain insights into 2 key questions: 1) Does the data give any insight into the characteristics of the virus? 2) Does the data identify risk points where countries need to be focused?

1) Does the data give any insight into the characteristics of the virus?

When looking at defining characteristics of the virus, we looked at contagion spread rates, average infection rates of the population and death rates. Chart 1, which shows cumulative cases over time, suggests that this is a highly infectious virus that will follow an exponential growth trend if it can take root in a population. We also see in chart 6 that the death rate is relatively stable around 3 deaths per thousand cases, though there are significant outliers.

The highest rate of infection, as seen in chart 3 (top 20 countries by cases per population) appear to be in the 2 to 10 people per thousand. Countries which have significant infection levels but are not yet in this range need to take precautions to avoid moving into that range and all countries need to ensure their medical systems can eventually handle a caseload equivalent to that. Because this is cumulative cases, case smoothing through social distancing endeavours may spread the infection rate at any one point in time out sufficiently to avoid overloading healthcare systems.

2) Does the data identify risk points where countries need to be focused? In terms of identifying risk, we looked at the data to answer the following 2 questions:

a) Are there countries which are below the current infection rate which migh be at risk?

The top 20 countries account for 89% of cases and 95% death. Unfortunately, some of the largest population countries in the world (India, Indonesia, Pakistan) do not show up on the list of countries with a high number of cases, which suggests that the cumulative number of cases worldwide may increase significantly should the virus take root and spread through these countries. The 3 listed countries are not countries known for having high quality and widely available healthcare, which increases the risk of catastrophic infection and death rates.

b) Are there countries which are trending higher on infection rate but lower on deaths?

Chart 4 shows that the United States stands out for being significantly lower on than the average on numbers of deaths vs numbers of cases, suggesting either a better than normal healthcare system or a need to prepare for an oncoming wave of fatalities. For most part, the other high infection rate countries are trending above the deaths per case average line.

1 & 2 Data Preparation and exploration¶

I combined data exploration and preparation as I continued to modify and massage data throughout the exploration, blurring the lines between data exploration and preparation. As I explored and identified new potential venues of investigation, I would go back to modify the data to support the new exploration.

In the first look at the data, it becomes obvious that the data is created in an additive manner, ie new data is added as it arrives. The first step is to add in a date field in date-time format and then sort the data by country into ascending date so that the data can be used as a time series

Review of null data shows that null records show up in geoId, ctycode and popData2018. Since we have country names we can ignore the ctycode and geoID as these can be engineered from the country names if needed. Of more concern is the missing population data. Further digging reveals that the records are focused on 5 countries: Anguilla (pop: 17400); Bonaire, Saint Eustatius and Saba (aka Carribean Netherlands, pop: 25,157); Czechia (new name of the Czech replublic, 10.6M); Eritrea (3.4M) ; and FalklandIslands(Malvinas) (pop:2,840) The null values were manually corrected to complete the data set.

The death rate growth number was also calculated as this allows us to calculate the velocity of the growth, not just raw growth (velocity is the growth rate of the speed). This allows us to tell if the speed of the virus spread is increasing or decreasing.

The cumulative death rate and case rate will allow us to look at the percent of the total population infected and killed by the virus. We can then chart in section 3 the mortality rate by country.

A summary by country indicates that there are 206 countries in the dataset, and that the top 20 countries make up 89% of cases and 95% of all deaths. Unfortunately, some of the largest population countries in the world (India, Indonesia, Pakistan) are not on the list, suggesting that this virus still has a way to go and that high population countries which are low on the list (China, Brazil) need to stay vigilant to avoid further infection of their population.

# Calculate rate of growth of cases and deaths
df=pd.DataFrame(data)
df['case_growth']=df['cases'].groupby(level='cnty').diff()
df['death_growth']=df['deaths'].groupby(level='cnty').diff()

# Replace Nulls with 0
df['case_growth']=df['case_growth'].fillna(0)
df['death_growth']=df['death_growth'].fillna(0)

data=df

3. Data Visualization¶

Chart 1, cases by month, shows the sharp difference between China and the rest of the world. While China's cases have flatlined, the rest of the world continues to grow. The sharp rise of United States cases is particularly concerning. Chart 2, deaths per month, shows the death rate mirroring the infection rate. This is studied in more detail in the following charts.

Chart 3 shows the top 20 countries by cases as a percent of the population. This chart provides a high-level view on how bad infection levels can get if protective measures are not taken.

Chart 4, The cases vs deaths chart shows an even more concerning picture: despite its high case rate, the US is below the regression line and outside the 90% confidence range, which suggests that if the CoVid death rate remains consistent globally, the US is facing an impending wave of fatalities. (Chart 5 is a log version of chart 4 for data discovery purposes).

Chart 6 summarizes a lot of the insight from the above charts, it is the “Executive Summary” chart. It shows the cases per million population vs deaths per case. The size of the dot is size of the country’s population. Many countries are below the average for cases per population, showing the countries at risk. It also shows that the death rate is relatively predictable at approximately 3 per 1000 cases, though significant outliers exist.

# Deaths vs cases
# When comparing cases vs deaths it appears that the USA is tracking below the regression line, which is either an indication
# of a better medical system, healthier population (or combination of both) or impending increase in deaths to bring the 
# deathrate closer to the norm.It should slo be noted that above 50,000 cases, the death rate to cases becomes highly 
# unpredictable with current data, with most of the cases falling outside the confidence range.
# I experimeted with taken the log of the axes and utilizing a log scale on the X-axis appeared to bring the data points closest
# to the regression line and the confidence interval. This seems to suggest that the log of cases is a potential predictor of Y.


df=pd.DataFrame(data)

# This code groups the data by country and then take the max of the index (in this case date and country) to give the data 
# for the latest date.
df_latestdata=df.loc[df.groupby(["cnty"])["date"].idxmax()]
df_casevsdeath=df_latestdata[["cum_cases","cum_deaths"]].copy()
casevsdeath=df_casevsdeath

# Plot figure using pyplot

# Deaths per case vs Cases per population with country population for marker size

# This chart indicates several things:
# 1) The death rate per case appears to be around 0.03 per case or 3% of confirmed cases. (This lines up with published info)
# 2) There are significant outliers which suggests either poor healthcare or lack of testing in some countries.
#    - If we llok at trends and see the death rate climbing over time, it could suggest a mutation to kae the virus deadlier
# 3) There are a lot of large population countries with lower cases per population. These countries need to start taking 
#    precautions now to prevent a large outbreak.

df=pd.DataFrame(data)
df_latestdata=df.loc[df.groupby(["cnty"])["date"].idxmax()]
df_chartdata=df_latestdata[["country","deaths_per_case","cum_cases","popData2018"]].copy()
df_chartdata["PopM"]=(df_chartdata["popData2018"]/1000000)
df_chartdata["CasePerKPop"]=(df_chartdata["cum_cases"]/(df_chartdata["popData2018"]/1000))
df_chartdata=df_chartdata[df_chartdata.country !='Cases_on_an_international_conveyance_Japan']
chartdata=df_chartdata

x = (chartdata["deaths_per_case"])
y = np.log(chartdata["CasePerKPop"], dtype='float64')
s = chartdata["PopM"]

plt.scatter(x,y,s)
plt.title("Chart 6 Deaths Per Case vs Cases per Pop (M)")
plt.xlabel("deaths_per_case")
plt.ylabel("Case Per Pop(M)")

4. Data Scaling¶

For the purpose of the data scaling exercise, we will continue the scaling exercise started in the cases vs deaths chart. For this exercise, we use 4 scalers to transform the data. Standard Scaler Normalizer Min Max Scaler Max Abs Scaler

None of the scaling appears to have generated a regression that improved over the log of cumulative cases approach taken in the charting section.
